    "reasoning": "To implement a 4-bit adder with full adders that produces a 5-bit output including the overflow bit, I need to follow these steps:\n1. Understand that we're adding two 4-bit numbers (x and y) to produce a 5-bit result (sum).\n2. A full adder takes three inputs: two bits to be added and a carry-in, producing a sum bit and a carry-out.\n3. I will create a 4-bit ripple-carry adder using four full adders.\n4. The carry-out from the most significant bit (MSB) will be the fifth bit of the output sum, representing overflow.\n5. I'll construct the adder bit by bit from LSB to MSB, propagating carries.\n\nFor the implementation:\n- I'll declare internal signals for carry bits between full adders.\n- Each full adder is constructed using XOR gates for sum and AND/OR gates for carry.\n- The final sum includes 4 bits from individual additions plus 1 overflow bit.\n\nSyntax considerations:\n- All signals must be declared as 'logic'.\n- Use 'always @(*)' for combinational logic.\n- Use proper bit indexing: x[0], x[1], etc., not x[1:2].\n- Use concatenation when needed: {a, b} instead of x[1:2] for reverse order.",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input [3:0] x,\n    input [3:0] y,\n    output [4:0] sum\n);\n\n    // Internal signals for carry propagation\n    logic c0, c1, c2, c3;\n\n    // Full Adder for LSB (bit 0)\n    assign sum[0] = x[0] ^ y[0] ^ c0;\n    assign c0 = (x[0] & y[0]) | (x[0] & c0) | (y[0] & c0);\n\n    // Full Adder for bit 1\n    assign sum[1] = x[1] ^ y[1] ^ c1;\n    assign c1 = (x[1] & y[1]) | (x[1] & c0) | (y[1] & c0);\n\n    // Full Adder for bit 2\n    assign sum[2] = x[2] ^ y[2] ^ c2;\n    assign c2 = (x[2] & y[2]) | (x[2] & c1) | (y[2] & c1);\n\n    // Full Adder for bit 3 (MSB)\n    assign sum[3] = x[3] ^ y[3] ^ c3;\n    assign c3 = (x[3] & y[3]) | (x[3] & c2) | (y[3] & c2);\n\n    // Overflow bit is the carry-out from the MSB\n    assign sum[4] = c3;\n\nendmodule"
